<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-04-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-04-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="197" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d197">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Burnley</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Seward</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-04-03"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 3, 1865.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Sir</hi>: Viscount Monck informs me by
                            telegraph that the Canadian courts had decided that the St. Albans
                            raiders could not be surrendered, and they were consequently
                            discharged.</p>
                        <p>It appears, however, that the governor general directed their immediate
                            rearrest on a charge of violating the Queen’s neutrality.</p>
                        <p>Believe me to remain, my dear sir, yours, very faithfully,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>J. HUME BURNLEY.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>Hon. <hi rend="smallcaps">William H. Seward,</hi>
                                <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c</hi>.</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>